 200 -    def writeiniFile(self, filename, section, option, value): 

 201          """  
 202          Writes the given settings to the given settings filename. If the section does not exist in the  
 203          settings file then it will be created. The file is assumed to be a .ini file. This method is 
 204          a modified version of the one found on the following website:  
 205          U{http://bytes.com/topic/python/answers/627791-writing-file-using-configparser} 
 206           
 207          @type filename: string 
 208          @param filename: path to the settings file 
 209          @type section: string 
 210          @param section: section heading in the settings file 
 211          @param option: string 
 212          @param option: The option in the given section in the settings file that will be set 
 213          @param value: The value of the option we are saving.  
 214          """ 
 215          Config = None 
 216          Config = ConfigParser.ConfigParser() 
 217          Config.read(filename) 
 218          if not Config.has_section( section ): #create the section 
 219              Config.add_section(section) 
 220          Config.set(section, option, value) 
 221          Config.write(open(filename,'w'))

 225 -    def ConfigSectionMap(self, Config, section): 

 226          """ 
 227          This method has been implemented based on the following exmaple,  
 228          U{http://wiki.python.org/moin/ConfigParserExamples}. 
 229           
 230          @param Config: ConfigParser instance that has already read the given settings filename. 
 231          @type section: string 
 232          @param section: Section that you want to get all of the elements of from the settings  
 233                          file that has been read by the Config parser and passed in as Config. 
 234          @rtype: Dictionary 
 235          @return: Dictionary where they keys are the options in the given section and the values  
 236                   are the corresponding settings value. 
 237          """ 
 238          dict1 = {} 
 239          options = Config.options(section) 
 240          for option in options: 
 241              try: 
 242                  dict1[option] = Config.get(section,option) 
 243                  if( dict1[option] == 1): 
 244                      print "Skipped loading option: %s" %option 
 245              except: 
 246                  print "Cannot load settings file. Crash on %s"%option 
 247                  dict1[option] = None 
 248          return dict1

 946          '''reset the values in the option menu

 948          if index is given, set the value of the menu to 
 949          the option at the given index. This code was modified from code found on stack overflow question: 
 950          U{http://stackoverflow.com/questions/7393430/how-can-i-dynamic-populate-an-option-widget-in-tkinter-depending-on-a-choice-fro}

 961          menu = om["menu"]

 964              menu.add_command(label=string,

 966                                      variable.set(value))

 968              variable.set(options[index])
